# 🎓 Analyze a Student Scores Dataset

This project focuses on analyzing a dataset of student scores to extract insights based on gender, class, and subject performance using tools like Excel, and basic formulas.

---

## 📊 Project Overview

Objective: 
To analyze and summarize student performance data and extract meaningful insights through Excel-based analytics.

Tools Used:
- Microsoft Excel
- Formulas: `AVERAGE`, `MAX`, `MIN`, `AVERAGEIF`, `COUNTIF`

---

## 📁 Dataset Fields

| Column        | Description                      |
|---------------|----------------------------------|
| Student Name  | Name of the student              |
| Gender        | Male / Female                    |
| Subject       | Subject tested                   |
| Score         | Marks obtained (0–100)           |
| Class         | e.g., 10A, 10B                   |

---

## 📐 Tasks Performed

| Task                                 | Formula / Tool Used                    |
|--------------------------------------|----------------------------------------|
| Total number of students             | `=COUNTA(A2:A11)`                      |
| Average score                        | `=AVERAGE(D2:D11)`                     |
| Highest score                        | `=MAX(D2:D11)`                         |
| Lowest score                         | `=MIN(D2:D11)`                         |
| Average score by Gender              | `=AVERAGEIF(B2:B11, "Male", D2:D11)`   |
| Count of students per class          | `=COUNTIF(E2:E11, "10A")`              |
| Top scorers per class                | Filter & sort (or use Pivot Table)     |

---

## 📈 Insights

- Female students had a higher average score.
- Class 10B had the highest number of students.
- The highest individual score was 95, achieved by John.

---

## 📂 Files Included

- `student_scores.csv` (Excel file with formulas)
- `Student Scores Summary Report.pdf` (PDF summary of findings)
- `student_scores_presentation.pptx` (Optional slides for presentation)

---

## 🚀 How to Use

1. Open the Excel file using Microsoft Excel.
2. Explore the formulas used in the analysis.
3. Use slicers or filters to explore custom views.

